---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
    title="About Me"
    description="MSc Physics student at the University of Münster, working on electron-pion separation using the TRD in the ALICE experiment at CERN."
    pubDate={new Date('February 24 2026')}
    heroImage="/about-hero.jpg"
>

<style>
    .about-content h2 {
        font-size: 1.3rem;
        font-weight: 700;
        margin: 2rem 0 0.75rem;
        color: #111;
    }
    .about-content p {
        color: #444;
        line-height: 1.78;
        margin-bottom: 1rem;
    }
    .about-content ul {
        margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 1.2rem;
        color: #444;
        line-height: 1.8;
    }
    .about-content a {
        color: #0070f3;
        text-decoration: none;
    }
    .about-content a:hover {
        text-decoration: underline;
    }
    .info-grid {
        display: grid;
        grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
        gap: 12px;
        margin: 1.5rem 0;
    }
    @media (max-width: 540px) {
        .info-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    }
    .info-card {
        background: #f7f8fa;
        border: 1px solid #e8e8e8;
        border-radius: 12px;
        padding: 14px 16px;
    }
    .info-card-label {
        font-size: 0.7rem;
        font-weight: 700;
        text-transform: uppercase;
        letter-spacing: 0.08em;
        color: #0070f3;
        margin-bottom: 4px;
    }
    .info-card-value {
        font-size: 0.9rem;
        color: #111;
        font-weight: 500;
        line-height: 1.5;
    }
    .info-card-sub {
        font-size: 0.78rem;
        color: #888;
        margin-top: 2px;
    }
    .contact-row {
        display: flex;
        gap: 12px;
        flex-wrap: wrap;
        margin-top: 0.75rem;
    }
    .contact-btn {
        display: inline-flex;
        align-items: center;
        gap: 6px;
        background: #0070f3;
        color: white !important;
        padding: 9px 18px;
        border-radius: 10px;
        font-size: 0.88rem;
        font-weight: 600;
        text-decoration: none !important;
        transition: background 0.2s;
    }
    .contact-btn:hover { background: #005bb5 !important; }
    .contact-btn.secondary {
        background: white;
        color: #333 !important;
        border: 1px solid #ddd;
    }
    .contact-btn.secondary:hover { background: #f5f5f5 !important; }
</style>

<div class="about-content">

    <p>
        I'm <strong>Madhva Fakare</strong>, a Master's student in Physics at the 
        <strong>University of Münster</strong>, Germany. Originally from India, I moved to 
        Germany to pursue experimental particle physics — and ended up working on one of the 
        most complex detectors ever built.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
        <div class="info-card">
            <div class="info-card-label">Education</div>
            <div class="info-card-value">MSc Physics</div>
            <div class="info-card-sub">University of Münster, Germany</div>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
            <div class="info-card-label">Experiment</div>
            <div class="info-card-value">ALICE · LHC · CERN</div>
            <div class="info-card-sub">Run 3 · Pb+Pb at √s = 5.5 TeV</div>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
            <div class="info-card-label">Thesis Focus</div>
            <div class="info-card-value">Electron-Pion Separation</div>
            <div class="info-card-sub">TRD · Boosted Decision Trees</div>
        </div>
        <div class="info-card">
            <div class="info-card-label">Tools</div>
            <div class="info-card-value">O2Physics · ROOT · C++</div>
            <div class="info-card-sub">Python · Git · lxplus / CVMFS</div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>What I Work On</h2>
    <p>
        My thesis focuses on <strong>electron-pion separation</strong> using the Transition 
        Radiation Detector (TRD) inside ALICE. ALICE is designed to study the 
        quark-gluon plasma — a state of matter that existed microseconds after the Big Bang — 
        by smashing lead nuclei together at nearly the speed of light.
    </p>
    <p>
        The TRD distinguishes particle types based on the transition radiation they emit 
        passing through alternating materials. My job is to build a machine learning pipeline 
        that uses these signals to separate electrons from pions as accurately as possible, 
        which matters for downstream physics measurements.
    </p>

    <h2>Day-to-Day</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Writing analysis code in <strong>C++</strong> within the O2Physics framework on CERN's lxplus servers</li>
        <li>Building ROOT macros to explore TRD detector signals across time bins (Q0, Q1, Q2)</li>
        <li>Training <strong>Boosted Decision Trees</strong> on real Run 3 collision data for particle ID</li>
        <li>Navigating the AO2D file format and linking track parameters to Monte Carlo truth labels</li>
        <li>Using CVMFS to access pre-compiled O2Physics without 24-hour local builds</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        The full analysis lives on GitHub: 
        <a href="https://github.com/madhva8/alice-trd-analysis" target="_blank">alice-trd-analysis</a>
    </p>

    <h2>Background</h2>
    <p>
        I completed my undergraduate Physics studies in India before coming to Münster. 
        The jump from coursework to real experimental data has been steep — ROOT, a 
        million-line codebase like O2Physics, actual LHC collision data. But the problems 
        are real and the data is real, and that makes all the difference.
    </p>
    <p>
        The detector signals I work with came from actual lead-lead collisions at 5.5 TeV — 
        conditions that briefly recreate the state of the universe a few microseconds after 
        the Big Bang. That's hard to get tired of.
    </p>

    <h2>Beyond Physics</h2>
    <p>
        I'm interested in how AI tools can speed up scientific workflows. There's a 
        <a href="/assistant">Physics AI Assistant</a> built into this site, pre-loaded with 
        my project context for quick questions while I work. I also write occasional 
        <a href="/blog">blog posts</a> about things I figured out the hard way in ROOT or 
        O2Physics — mostly so I don't forget, but hopefully useful to others too.
    </p>

    <h2>Get in Touch</h2>
    <p>Working on ALICE, particle ID, or ROOT/O2Physics? Happy to talk.</p>
    <div class="contact-row">
        <a href="mailto:madhva.fakare@cern.ch" class="contact-btn">
            ✉ madhva.fakare@cern.ch
        </a>
        <a href="https://github.com/madhva8" target="_blank" class="contact-btn secondary">
            ⌥ GitHub
        </a>
    </div>

</div>

</Layout>
